  "prompt": "Is power steering fluid the same as brake fluid?",
  "response": "No, power steering fluid and brake fluid are not the same, and they are not interchangeable. They serve different purposes and have different compositions suited to their respective systems.\n\n### 1. **Power Steering Fluid:**\n   - **Purpose:** Power steering fluid is used in the power steering system to assist in steering by transmitting hydraulic pressure, making it easier to turn the steering wheel.\n   - **Composition:** Power steering fluids are typically mineral oil-based or synthetic-based, and their formulation varies depending on the vehicle manufacturer. Some vehicles use automatic transmission fluid (ATF) in place of dedicated power steering fluid.\n   - **Properties:** It is designed to withstand high hydraulic pressures and provide lubrication for the power steering pump and components.\n\n### 2. **Brake Fluid:**\n   - **Purpose:** Brake fluid is used in the hydraulic brake system to transfer force from the brake pedal to the brake components (calipers or wheel cylinders), enabling the vehicle to stop.\n   - **Composition:** Brake fluid is typically glycol-based (DOT 3, DOT 4, DOT 5.1) or silicone-based (DOT 5). It is specifically formulated to handle extreme heat, resist compression, and maintain its properties under high-pressure conditions.\n   - **Properties:** Brake fluid has a high boiling point to prevent vaporization in the brake system, which could lead to brake failure. It is also hygroscopic, meaning it absorbs moisture from the air over time.\n\n### Key Differences:\n- **Function:** Power steering fluid is for assisting steering, while brake fluid is for braking.\n- **Compatibility:** Mixing these fluids or using the wrong one can damage the system, reduce performance, or lead to safety hazards.\n- **Performance Requirements:** Brake fluid must handle higher pressures and temperatures compared to power steering fluid.\n\nAlways refer to your vehicle\u2019s owner\u2019s manual to determine the correct fluid type for each system. Using the wrong fluid can compromise system performance and safety.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
